---
import BaseLayout from '../layouts/BaseLayout.astro';

const plans = [
  {
    name: 'Pilot',
    audience: 'For teams validating SNADLY on one real source system.',
    details: [
      'Profile source data and infer relationships',
      'Generate a first warehouse model, tests, and documentation',
      'Review output together before anything scales',
    ],
    cta: 'Book a pilot',
  },
  {
    name: 'Team',
    audience: 'For BI teams and analysts turning recurring source data into trusted models.',
    details: [
      'Repeatable warehouse builds and report generation',
      'Standard dbt output your team can inspect and own',
      'Pricing aligned to build activity, not passive viewers',
    ],
    cta: 'Discuss team use',
  },
  {
    name: 'Partner',
    audience: 'For consultancies using SNADLY inside client delivery workflows.',
    details: [
      'White-label output in your house style',
      'Review flows that keep consultants fluent in the model',
      'Commercial terms matched to client delivery volume',
    ],
    cta: 'Talk partnership',
  },
];
---

<BaseLayout
  title="Pricing | SNADLY"
  description="SNADLY pricing is scoped around the work being built: pilots, team use, and partner delivery."
>
  <section class="hero">
    <p class="eyebrow">Pricing</p>
    <h1>Pricing that follows the work, not every dashboard viewer.</h1>
    <p class="lede">
      SNADLY is priced around warehouse builds, source complexity, and delivery
      workflow. We keep the first engagement scoped so you can judge the output
      on real data before committing to a broader rollout.
    </p>
    <div class="actions">
      <a class="button" href="mailto:adrian.white@gmail.com">Start with your data</a>
      <a
        class="button button-secondary"
        href="https://www.loom.com/share/4c05501e9fa14edd97f10663f32faa7d"
        target="_blank"
        rel="noopener noreferrer"
      >
        Watch demo
      </a>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="section">
    <div class="price-grid">
      {plans.map((plan) => (
        <article class="price-card">
          <div>
            <p class="eyebrow">{plan.name}</p>
            <h2>{plan.name}</h2>
            <p>{plan.audience}</p>
          </div>
          <ul>
            {plan.details.map((item) => <li>{item}</li>)}
          </ul>
          <a class="button button-secondary" href="mailto:adrian.white@gmail.com">{plan.cta}</a>
        </article>
      ))}
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="section section-muted split">
    <div>
      <p class="eyebrow">How we scope</p>
      <h2>Start with the smallest useful proof.</h2>
      <p>
        The right first step is one real data source, one useful business
        question, and one output your team can inspect. If the generated models,
        tests, lineage, and documentation are not useful, there is no reason to
        expand.
      </p>
    </div>
    <aside class="note">
      <h3>Common pricing inputs</h3>
      <p>Number of source systems, model complexity, refresh frequency, review requirements, and whether the output is used internally or inside a client delivery process.</p>
    </aside>
  </section>
</BaseLayout>
